(42, 19, 39, 43, 12, 19, 19, 'rebuke thy disciples', 'Pharisees'' Reactions to Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the Pharisees'' concern over Jesus'' growing influence. In Luke, they ask Jesus to rebuke his disciples, while in John, they lament that ''the world is gone after him.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 39, 44, 4, 16, 18, 'rebuke thy disciples', 'Opposition to Jesus'' Followers', 'This connection highlights the opposition faced by Jesus and his disciples. In both passages, there is a call to silence those proclaiming Jesus'' name, reflecting a consistent theme of resistance from religious authorities.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 39, 59, 4, 5, 5, 'rebuke thy disciples', 'Connection of Envy and Rebuke', 'This connection highlights the theme of envy present in both passages. In Luke, the Pharisees express discontent with the disciples'' praise, while James addresses the spirit''s envy within believers.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 39, 40, 21, 15, 16, 'rebuke thy disciples', 'Praise and Rebuke Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of praise in both passages. In Luke, the Pharisees ask Jesus to rebuke his disciples for their praise, while in Matthew, the chief priests question Jesus about the children''s praise, which he defends.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
