(42, 19, 40, 40, 3, 9, 9, 'stones would immediately cry out', 'Connection of Stones in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of stones being used by God to fulfill His purposes. Both passages emphasize God''s ability to raise up children or praise from stones, indicating His sovereignty over creation.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 40, 19, 96, 11, 11, NULL, 'Creation''s Response to Praise', 'This connection highlights the theme of creation responding to divine glory. Both passages emphasize that even inanimate objects, like stones and the sea, express joy and praise.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 40, 19, 98, 7, 9, 'the stones would immediately cry out', 'Creation''s Response to God', 'This connection highlights the theme of creation responding to God''s presence. In both passages, the stones and the natural elements express joy and recognition of the Lord''s authority.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 40, 40, 27, 51, 54, 'the stones would immediately cry out', 'Connection of Creation''s Response', 'This connection highlights the theme of creation responding to significant events. In Luke, the stones would cry out if the people were silent, while in Matthew, the rocks rent during the earthquake, indicating a response to Jesus'' death.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 40, 61, 2, 6, 6, 'the stones would immediately cry out', 'Silence and Judgment Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of silence and the inevitability of judgment. In Luke, the stones would cry out if the people were silent, indicating that creation itself responds to truth, while in 2 Peter, the destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah serves as a warning against ungodliness, suggesting that silence in the face of wrongdoing leads to judgment.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
